 in the music industry to the structural upheaval created by urban redevelopment in major American cities. Dale Chapman draws from political and critical theory, oral history, and the public and trade press, making this a persuasive and compelling work for scholars across music, industry, and cultural studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 0aJazzxEconomic aspects. 0aJazzxHistory and criticism. 0aJazzxSocial aspects. 0aMusic-halls (Variety-theaters, cabarets, etc.)zCaliforniaxHistory. 0aSound recording industryxEconomic aspects. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Jazz.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018z978311063539308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2018z978311066767708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018z978311065859040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520968219423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/doc/cover/9780520968219.jpg  a978-3-11-063539-3  UC Press eBook-Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  a978-3-11-065859-0  UCal Press eBook Package Frontlist 2017-2018c2017d2018  a978-3-11-066767-7  UC Press eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles